    "contents" : "---\ntitle: Investigating the association between the child's demographic characteristics\n  and the mother's soap use practices\noutput:\n  html_document: default\n  pdf_document: default\n---\n\n```{r setup, include=FALSE}\nknitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, \n                      warning = FALSE,\n                      message = FALSE)\n```\n\n\n\n## Motivation\n\nIn Bangladesh, although there has been a steady progress in reducing gender inequality in different sectors, there is still inequality in some sectors like the health sector. For instance, the difference in child mortality between males and females is high, where female child mortality is higher than that of their male counterparts (Ferdaush and Rahman, 2011). In light of this issue, we aim to examine whether there is gender bias in maternal health behavior (for example, using soap when handwashing after defecation and using soap when washing clothes) during the child's early years of development. In addition, there are many studies suggesting that the first two years of a child's life are crucial in determining its well-being in adulthood (Case and Paxson, 2010). It would be interesting to examine whether maternal health habits differ in the child's first two years of life compared to the child's later years of development.\n\n## Data: SES_Wash.csv\n(Original source: Data obtained from https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5344309/)\n\nData for 10,478 children under 5 years old were collected in Bangladesh between February and November 2013. We'll use these data to examine the relationship between mothers' use of soap during handwashing and washing clothes, and children's demographic variables such as age and sex. All of the subjects in this data set are from a variety of regions in Bangladesh and data were collected using a national survey.\n\n## Questions of Interest\n\nGiven these data and the context, two questions of interest are:\n\n1. Is there any association between child's sex and the mother's practice of using soap during handwashing after defecation or using soap when washing clothes? \n\n2. Do these habits differ between the child's first two years of life and later childhood years (ages 3 to 5)? \n\n\nTherefore, the variables of interest are *wash1_a*, which takes the value 1 if the mothers used soap when washing their clothes and 0 if they did not, *wash6_a*, which takes the value 1 if the mothers used soap when washing their hands after defecating and 0 if they did not, *csex* refers to child's sex which takes the value Male or Female, and *age*, which lists the child's age in months. In this analysis, we'll designate children of age 24 months or younger as \"Age 0-2\" and those older than 24 months as \"Age 3-5\".\n\n\n\n## Instructions\n\nMake sure to install the following packages using the install.packages() function, then load the corresponding libraries. \n\n```{r}\nlibrary(dplyr) #Adds extra data cleaning functionality\nlibrary(epitools) #Adds odds ratio and relative risk functions\n```\nNext, read the CSV data into R, which we'll call *washing*.\n\n```{r}\nwashing <- read.csv(\"SES_Wash.csv\") \nhead(washing) # Shows the first six rows of the data set\n```\n\n\n## Exploring the Data\n\nLet's begin by collapsing the data set into the four variables of interest: *wash1_a* *wash6_a*, *csex*, and *age*. We'll use the select() function from the *dplyr* library to achieve this.\n\n\n```{r}\nwashing.subset <- washing %>%\n  select(wash1_a, wash6_a, csex, age)\n```\n\nNext, we'll individually explore the four variables of interest to determine if there are any missing values or irregularities. Since washing clothes with soap (*wash1_a*), washing with soap after defecation (*wash6_a*), and child's sex assigned at birth (*csex*) are categorical variables, we'll use the table function to create contingency tables telling us the number of times the given variable took each of the possible values. Since child's *age* is quantitative, we'll use the summary function to calculate the five number summary (min, max, first and third quartiles, median) plus the mean of ages.\n\n\\pagebreak\n\n```{r}\ntable(washing.subset$wash1_a) # Washing clothes with soap\ntable(washing.subset$wash6_a) # Washing hands with soap after defecation\ntable(washing.subset$csex) # Child's sex\nsummary(washing.subset$age) # Child's age\n```\n\nThere are significantly more people who wash their clothes with soap than those who do not. There appears to be slightly more people who wash their hands after defecating than those who do not. Additionally, there are an approximately equal number of males and females in this data set. Ages range from newborn ($\\text{age} = 0.10$ months old) to children of age 5 ($\\text{age} = 59.90$ months). \n\n## Data Cleaning\n\nAs part of our questions of interest, we are interested in investigating a possible association between the mother's practice of washing hands or clothes and the child's stage of development (age 0 to 2 compared to age 3 to 5). Thus, we need to change the *age* variable into a categorical variable. To add a new variable to our dataset, we will use the mutate() function from the *dplyr* library.\n\n```{r}\nwashing.subset <- washing.subset %>%\n  mutate(child_stage = ifelse(age <= 24, #Checks if the child age is <= 24 months.\n                       \"Age 0-2\", #If it is, then age 0-2. \n                       \"Age 3-5\")) #Else, then age 3-5.\n```\n\nOur new variable, *child_stage*, takes the value *Age 0-2* if the child is of age 24 months or below, and *Age 3-5* otherwise. We will use this new *child_stage* variable later in our analysis.\n\nNext, in order to make the *wash6_a* variable easier to interpret at a glance (and to match the coding of the *wash1_a* variable), we will use the recode function to change the values of 0 to *No* and change the values of 1 to *Yes*.\n\n```{r}\n\nwashing.subset$wash6_a <- recode(washing.subset$wash6_a,\n                                 `0` = \"No\",\n                                 `1` = \"Yes\")\n\n```\n\nFinally, we'll rename all of the variables to make them easier to identify.\n\n```{r}\nnames(washing.subset) <- c(\"Soap.With.Clothes\",\n                           \"Soap.After.Defecating\",\n                           \"Sex\",\n                           \"Age\",\n                           \"Stage.Of.Development\")\n```\n\n\n\n## Data Analysis\n\n### Investigating the Association Between Soap Use after Defecation and Child's Sex\n\nLet's construct a contingency table of child's sex and mother's soap use after defecating to examine any possible patterns. The resulting table is below. Since our outcome of interest is mother's use of soap for handwashing after defecating, we'll switch the order of rows in the table (add [c(2,1),]) so that \"Yes\" is in the first row. \n\n```{r}\nsoap.use.defecation.by.sex <- table(washing.subset$Soap.After.Defecating, \n                                    washing.subset$Sex)[c(2,1),]\n                                  \nsoap.use.defecation.by.sex\n```\n\nAcross both child sexes, mothers are likely to wash their hands with soap after defecating. It is not immediately clear from the table if there is any association between child's sex and the mother's habit of handwashing with soap after defecation. \n\nIn order to determine if there is any association between these two variables, we can utilize a $\\chi^2$ contingency test (also known as a $\\chi^2$ test for association or correlation).\n\n```{r}\nsaveChiTest <- chisq.test(soap.use.defecation.by.sex)\nsaveChiTest\n```\n\nThe resulting $p$-value is large, so there is no evidence of an association between child's sex and whether or not mothers wash their hands with soap after defecating. \n\nThe results of the $\\chi^2$ contingency test are valid under the assumptions that no more than 20\\% of the cells can have an expected frequency less than five, and no cell can have an expected frequency less than one. These assumptions are met based on the expected frequency values below.\n\n```{r}\nsaveChiTest$expected\n```\n\nA corresponding mosaic plot helps to visualize this lack of association.\n```{r}\nmosaicplot(t(soap.use.defecation.by.sex), \n           col = c(\"firebrick\", \"goldenrod1\"), #Adds colors\n           cex.axis = 1, #To magnify axis notation\n           xlab = \"Child's Sex\", \n           ylab = \"Soap Use When Handwashing After Defecation\", \n           main = \"\")\n```\n\nTo better quantify this lack of association, we'll next calculate the odds ratio of using soap after defecation.\n\n```{r}\noddsratio(soap.use.defecation.by.sex, \n          method = \"wald\")$measure[-1,] #Extracts only the ouput necessary to identify odds ratio\n```\n\nThe odds ratio here of approximately 1.03 is a comparison of the proportion of *female* children  whose mothers use soap to wash their hands after defecation relative to the proportion of *male* children  whose mothers use soap to wash their hands after defecation. Since this odds ratio is very close to 1, it suggests that female children are just as likely to have mothers washing their hands with soap after defecation relative to male children.\n\n\n### Investigating the Association Between Soap Use after Defecation and Child's Stage of Development\n\nNext, using the same approach, we'll examine a possible association between child's stage of development and the mother's habit of washing with soap after defecation.\n\n```{r}\nsoap.use.defecation.by.age <- table(washing.subset$Soap.After.Defecating,\n                                    washing.subset$Stage.Of.Development)[c(2,1),]\n\nsoap.use.defecation.by.age\n```\n\n\n```{r}\nsaveChiTest2 <- chisq.test(soap.use.defecation.by.age)\nsaveChiTest2\n```\n\nThe contingency table demonstrates---and the $\\chi^2$ contingency test confirms---that there is very little or no statistically significant evidence ($p$-value = .13) of an association between child's stage of development and maternal washing habits after defecating. \n\nThe results of the $\\chi^2$ contingency test are valid under the assumptions that no more than 20\\% of the cells can have an expected frequency less than five, and no cell can have an expected frequency less than one. These assumptions are met based on the values in the expected frequency table below. \n\n```{r}\nsaveChiTest2$expected\n```\n\nA mosaic plot again highlights this lack of association.\n\n```{r}\nmosaicplot(t(soap.use.defecation.by.age), \n           col = c(\"firebrick\", \"goldenrod1\"), #Adds colors\n           cex.axis = 1, #To magnify axis notation\n           xlab = \"Child's Stage of Development\",\n           ylab = \"Soap Use When Handwashing After Defecation\", \n           main = \"\")\n```\n\nThus, the results of the contingency test and this mosaic plot both suggest that there is lack of evidence showing association between child's stage of development and the mother's use of soap after defecation.\n\nTo better quantify this lack of association, we'll next calculate the odds ratio of using soap to wash hands after defecation.\n\n```{r}\noddsratio(soap.use.defecation.by.age, \n          method = \"wald\")$measure[-1,] #Extracts only the ouput necessary to identify odds ratio\n```\n\nThe odds ratio here of approximately 1.06 is a comparison of the proportion of children *aged 0 to 2* whose mothers use soap to wash their hands after defecation relative to the proportion of children *aged 3 to 5* whose mothers use soap to wash their hands after defecation. Since this odds ratio is close to 1, this suggests that children in their first two years of life are equally as likely to have mothers washing their hands with soap after defecation relative to children of age 3 to 5.\n\n\\pagebreak\n\n### Investigating the Association Between Soap Use When Washing Clothes and Child's Sex\n\nWe'll now take a similar approach to identify a possible association between child's sex and the mother's use of soap when washing clothes. First, we'll investigate whether the mother's use of soap when washing clothes differ by child's sex. Since our outcome of interest is mother's use of soap when washing clothes, we'll switch the order of rows in the table (add [c(2,1),]) so that \"Yes\" is in the first row. \n\n```{r}\nsoap.use.clothes.by.sex <- table(washing.subset$Soap.With.Clothes, \n                                 washing.subset$Sex)[c(2,1),]\n\nsoap.use.clothes.by.sex\n\nsaveChiTest3 <- chisq.test(soap.use.clothes.by.sex)\nsaveChiTest3\n```\n\nOnce again, the contingency table demonstrates --- and the $\\chi^2$ contingency test confirms --- that there is no statistically significant evidence of an association between child's sex and the mother's soap use when washing clothes. \n\nThe results of the $\\chi^2$ contingency test are valid under the assumptions that no more than 20\\% of the cells can have an expected frequency less than five, and no cell can have an expected frequency less than one. These assumptions are met based on the values in expected frequency table below. \n\n```{r}\nsaveChiTest3$expected\n```\n\n\nOnce again, the mosaic plot highlights this lack of association.\n\n```{r}\nmosaicplot(t(soap.use.clothes.by.sex), \n           col = c(\"firebrick\", \"goldenrod1\"), #Adds colors\n           cex.axis = 1, #To magnify axis notation\n           xlab = \"Child's Sex\",\n           ylab = \"Soap Use When Washing Clothes\", \n           main = \"\")\n\n```\n\nTo better quantify this lack of association, we'll next calculate the odds ratio of using soap to wash their clothes.\n\n```{r}\noddsratio(soap.use.clothes.by.sex, \n          method = \"wald\")$measure[-1,] #Extracts only the ouput necessary to identify odds ratio\n```\n\nThe odds ratio here of approximately 1.05 is a comparison of the proportion of *female* children  whose mothers use soap to wash their clothes relative to the proportion of *male* children  whose mothers use soap to wash their clothes. Since this odds ratio is very close to 1, it suggests that *female* children are just as likely to have mothers washing their clothes with soap relative to *male* children.\n\n### Investigating the Association Between Soap Use When Washing Clothes and Child's Stage of Development\n\nFinally, we'll investigate a potential association between child's stage of development and maternal habit of washing clothes with soap.\n\n```{r}\nsoap.use.clothes.by.age <- table(washing.subset$Soap.With.Clothes, \n                                 washing.subset$Stage.Of.Development)[c(2,1),]\n\nsoap.use.clothes.by.age\n\nsaveChiTest4 <- chisq.test(soap.use.clothes.by.age)\nsaveChiTest4 \n```\n\nGiven the very small $p$-value, there appears to be very strong evidence of an association between child's stage of development and the mother's use of soap when washing clothes. \n\nThe results of the $\\chi^2$ contingency test are valid under the assumptions that no more than 20\\% of the cells can have an expected frequency less than five, and no cell can have an expected frequency less than one. The expected frequency table below confirms that these assumptions are met.\n```{r}\nsaveChiTest4$expected\n```\n\n\nTo better understand the direction of this association, we'll construct a mosaic plot.\n\n```{r}\nmosaicplot(t(soap.use.clothes.by.age), \n           col = c(\"firebrick\", \"goldenrod1\"), #Adds colors\n           cex.axis = 1, #To magnify axis notation\n           xlab = \"Child's Stage of Development\",\n           ylab = \"Soap Use When Washing Clothes\", \n           main = \"\")\n\n```\n\nThe mosaic plot demonstrates that mothers with children who are *aged 0 to 2* are *more* likely to wash their clothes with soap than one would expect, and mothers with children who are *aged 3 to 5* are  *less* likely to wash their clothes with soap. \n\nTo better quantify this association, we'll next calculate the odds ratio and relative risk of using soap to wash clothes.\n\n```{r}\noddsratio(soap.use.clothes.by.age, \n          method = \"wald\")$measure[-1,] #Extracts only the ouput necessary to identify odds ratio\n```\n\nThe odds ratio here of approximately 1.27 is a comparison of the proportion of children *aged 0 to 2* whose mothers do use soap to wash their clothes relative to the proportion of children *aged 3 to 5* whose mothers do use soap to wash their clothes. Since this odds ratio is greater than 1, this suggests that children in their first two years of life are more likely (i.e., have higher odds) to have mothers washing their clothes with soap relative to children of aged 3 to 5.\n\nRelative risk is another method of quantifying the association seen here. The relative risk here is the ratio of the probability of mothers using soap to wash their clothes among children *aged 0 to 2* relative to the probability of mothers using soap to wash their clothes among children *aged 3 to 5*.\n\n\\pagebreak\n\n```{r}\nriskratio(soap.use.clothes.by.age, \n          method = \"wald\",\n          rev = \"both\")$measure[-1,] #Extracts only the ouput necessary to identify relative risk\n```\n\nThe relative risk here is approximately 1.16. Since this is greater than 1, this suggests that mothers are more likely to wash clothes with soap for the group of children who are *aged 0 to 2* relative to the group of children who are *aged 3 to 5*.\n\n## Conclusion\nBased on these results, we find little or no evidence of association between mother's soap use after defecating and the child's demographic characteristics such as sex and age (stage of development). We also do not find evidence of association between mother's soap use when washing clothes and child's sex. However, we do find evidence of an association between child's stage of development and the mother's use of soap when washing clothes. In particular,  children in their first two years of life have higher odds to have mothers washing their clothes with soap relative to children of aged 3 to 5. Further investigation may be necessary to determine what is driving this association.\n\n## References\n\nJannatul Ferdaush and K.M. Mustafizur Rahman, \"Gender Inequality in Bangladesh,\" *The Innovators*, October 2011. \n\nMohammad Jyoti Raihan, Fammida Dil Farzana, Sabihna Sultana, Md Ahshanul Haque, Ahmed Shafiqur Rahman, Jillian Waid, et al., \"Examining the relationship between socio-economic status, WASH practices and wasting,\" *PLoS ONE* 12(3), March 2017. \n\nAnne Case and C. Paxson, \"Causes and consequences of early-life health,\" *Demography* 2010 Mar; 47(Suppl 1): S65–S85.\n\n\n\n",
